1
00:00:00,858 --> 00:00:16,815
Foundation, Course 2, Talk 7 Paticcasumapada, the Wheel of Dependent Origination In the last attempt at describing the central teaching of the Buddha, I concentrated on how it works in daily life.

2
00:00:18,096 --> 00:00:29,547
After a reminder of what the links are in the wheel, I'd like to develop the historical process of the wheel, the process of habit-forming, the importance of the present moment, rebirth and its meaning,

3
00:00:30,051 --> 00:00:38,081
and finally to give some idea of what it is to be totally liberated, an Arahant or a Buddha, in terms of the wheel of dependent origination.

4
00:00:40,524 --> 00:00:49,393
The links of the wheel of dependent origination are made in a circular form to show the inevitable rounds of rebirth.

5
00:00:50,456 --> 00:00:54,219
So long as there is ignorance, the first link, the wheel, will always turn.

6
00:00:55,161 --> 00:01:01,029
Ignorance is the root cause, our not knowing why we are born, why we live and why we die.

7
00:01:02,009 --> 00:01:09,858
Because of this ignorance we attach to the sense world, the world of transient things, things that are not substantial or real in any permanent way.

8
00:01:10,960 --> 00:01:21,253
Because of this wrong attachment we have built up a whole battery of dependencies, of conditionings that cry out for satisfaction and lead us by the nose to seek that satisfaction.

9
00:01:22,870 --> 00:01:31,240
Even though we don't know why we are born, or why we live or why we die, indeed why we suffer, we still crave for life and birth with all that that means.

10
00:01:32,823 --> 00:01:35,987
These conditionings are the product of past decisions and actions.

11
00:01:36,748 --> 00:01:40,233
These volitional conditionings or formations are the second link.

12
00:01:41,415 --> 00:01:45,620
Once these two preconditions are there, the next five links come into being.

13
00:01:45,905 --> 00:02:02,221
The human being itself, with all its consciousnesses, its body and mind, the six senses, the ability through these senses to make contact with the world, and the feelings that these contacts produce in the body, perceived as either pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

14
00:02:04,805 --> 00:02:11,592
Once a human is endowed with these basic faculties, there is a reaction, a response to all the information coming in.

15
00:02:12,247 --> 00:02:16,032
This response is desire, whether it is a want or a don't want.

16
00:02:16,894 --> 00:02:23,842
And this desire becomes strong and produces an attachment, a grasping, an obsession, sometimes an uncontrollable craving.

17
00:02:25,125 --> 00:02:28,530
This leads to a decision, to an action, in order to fulfill that craving.

18
00:02:28,931 --> 00:02:29,711
We want to live.

19
00:02:30,772 --> 00:02:32,616
When death approaches, we clutch at life.

20
00:02:33,015 --> 00:02:34,878
A drowning man clutches at a straw.

21
00:02:35,736 --> 00:02:45,191
But once these three links are activated, the desire, the attachment and action arising out of these motivations, we can be assured of becoming.

22
00:02:45,211 --> 00:02:50,679
This becoming means that the cycle will all be repeated again in the future.

23
00:02:51,319 --> 00:02:57,429
This future is just this cycle of birth, growth, a momentary peak, then decay and death.

24
00:02:58,590 --> 00:03:05,219
These are the twelve links, the twelve consecutive causes and effects that produce the whole phenomena of birth and death.

25
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:12,764
If we now look at it from the point of view of karma, we shall see this historical process more clearly.

26
00:03:13,605 --> 00:03:16,489
The law of karma states that nothing happens without a cause.

27
00:03:17,909 --> 00:03:23,895
So it is the Buddha says, inconceivable is the beginning, O disciples, of this going on and on.

28
00:03:24,776 --> 00:03:26,598
The earliest point is not revealed.

29
00:03:28,039 --> 00:03:31,682
And just as the earliest point is not revealed, so an ending is incomprehensible.

30
00:03:32,063 --> 00:03:33,245
In fact, there is no ending.

31
00:03:33,585 --> 00:03:36,388
There is only escape, only liberation.

32
00:03:37,448 --> 00:03:44,194
To be clear how this liberation is to be achieved, we need to have understood how it is we keep on becoming.

33
00:03:45,656 --> 00:03:51,562
In any given moment in our lives, ignorance and past volitional intentioned conditionings are always with us.

34
00:03:52,603 --> 00:03:54,064
The ignorance is a passive thing.

35
00:03:54,885 --> 00:03:57,788
The problem is we don't know what it is we are ignorant of.

36
00:03:58,408 --> 00:04:00,752
That's a tautology I know, but it needs to be said.

37
00:04:01,932 --> 00:04:05,817
If we did know what we were ignorant of, we'd soon find a way to dispel it.

38
00:04:05,997 --> 00:04:07,117
We'd become wise.

39
00:04:07,925 --> 00:04:11,289
but we can take a middle position and acknowledge that we don't know everything.

40
00:04:12,371 --> 00:04:19,262
This attitude at least keeps us open-minded, keeps us searching, and open to information that might disagree with what we believe.

41
00:04:21,163 --> 00:04:23,687
In the Dhammapada, the Buddha is very clear on this.

42
00:04:24,829 --> 00:04:29,136
The fool, who knows he is a fool, can for that reason be a wise man.

43
00:04:30,057 --> 00:04:34,103
But a fool who thinks himself wise, that fool is a fool indeed.

44
00:04:35,084 --> 00:04:36,766
For fool, read Ignorance.

45
00:04:38,569 --> 00:04:55,156
Much of what we believe is simply blind acceptance of what we have been told, such as the belief that the human being is a complete whole and not a collection of integrated parts, or the belief that in the body and personality there is some substantial real everlasting soul or self or ego.

46
00:04:56,619 --> 00:05:03,209
This sort of belief based on ignorance, this delusion, causes us to behave in certain ways that reinforce that belief.

47
00:05:04,372 --> 00:05:12,240
Beliefs are self-fulfilling, since they perceive the world in a certain way, and that certain way blocks out any information that does not fit.

48
00:05:13,182 --> 00:05:14,442
This is what conditioning does.

49
00:05:17,346 --> 00:05:22,793
If we take one of the great evils in the world today, racism, this sort of mechanism becomes obvious.

50
00:05:24,274 --> 00:05:25,915
Racism is a worldwide phenomena.

51
00:05:26,216 --> 00:05:29,180
Anyone who travels will come up against it in all sorts of forms.

52
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:33,805
Each ethnic grouping presumes the other to be inferior by its own standards.

53
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:47,754
Very early on in life as children, the things our parents, friends and media say, the way they say whatever they say about the other so-called race, all conditions our childish, ignorant, not-knowing mind.

54
00:05:48,714 --> 00:05:50,476
The child simply does not know better.

55
00:05:51,798 --> 00:05:57,264
Later, that child acts upon that racist information and reinforces its own conditionings.

56
00:05:59,026 --> 00:06:01,367
I remember as a child being taunted by other children.

57
00:06:01,968 --> 00:06:02,829
I was born in Italy.

58
00:06:03,247 --> 00:06:07,336
And when I went to school, my English was very poor, so the other children would make fun of me.

59
00:06:08,499 --> 00:06:20,665
One of the things they'd do is turn me round to look at the yellow stripe down my back, since all Italians, because of Mussolini's invasion of a defenceless Ethiopia and the later miserable war record, were supposed to be cowards.

60
00:06:21,026 --> 00:06:21,747
They were yellow.

61
00:06:23,009 --> 00:06:24,771
Unfortunately, it didn't stop there.

62
00:06:25,372 --> 00:06:26,435
I was enculturated.

63
00:06:26,956 --> 00:06:29,961
By eight or nine, no one would have known me to be Italian.

64
00:06:30,322 --> 00:06:32,204
My English was English and my name was English.

65
00:06:32,584 --> 00:06:33,747
I looked and behaved English.

66
00:06:34,649 --> 00:06:36,932
Social pressure pushed me to assimilate.

67
00:06:38,355 --> 00:06:40,319
I wanted to be accepted by my peer group.

68
00:06:41,100 --> 00:06:42,942
I internalized their hatred of Italy.

69
00:06:43,824 --> 00:06:45,487
I was ashamed of my Italian origin.

70
00:06:46,168 --> 00:06:48,713
I was ashamed of being out with my Italian mother.

71
00:06:49,773 --> 00:06:55,980
By the age of 11, I remember taking distinct delight in making fun of the first West Indian who came to the school.

72
00:06:56,982 --> 00:07:01,927
There I was, turning the wheel of racial hatred, even though I myself had suffered from it.

73
00:07:03,569 --> 00:07:12,120
My subconscious unresolved anger at those who made fun of me found its sweet revenge in perpetrating the same violence on another entirely innocent.

74
00:07:13,622 --> 00:07:16,565
The effects of our conditioning can be extremely subtle.

75
00:07:16,586 --> 00:07:17,687
We simply don't know.

76
00:07:18,949 --> 00:07:24,036
There was a teacher I knew who blamed the inability of some Asians to draw in three dimensions on genetics.

77
00:07:25,218 --> 00:07:37,812
What this teacher was saying was that the skills that are obviously taught and learnt are already somehow pre-programmed by our genes, and that it was these genes that set one above the other, one race above another.

78
00:07:39,194 --> 00:07:47,504
Whether this sort of thinking manifests itself between different ethnic groups as racism, or between different classes of people in a society as classism,

79
00:07:47,975 --> 00:07:49,916
The Buddha made his position quite clear.

80
00:07:51,737 --> 00:07:58,904
The Brahmanical society of the Buddha's day had produced such a rigid caste system that it was impossible to move from one to the other.

81
00:07:59,625 --> 00:08:01,247
There was no social mobility.

82
00:08:02,327 --> 00:08:04,870
Each caste had a particular task apportioned to it.

83
00:08:05,651 --> 00:08:10,776
The Kshatriya caste, to which the Buddha himself belonged, were the warriors, rulers or governing class.

84
00:08:12,016 --> 00:08:16,581
Whether you had such capabilities or not, that's where you stayed if that's where you were born.

85
00:08:17,387 --> 00:08:22,052
You certainly couldn't do things ascribed to other castes, such as becoming a merchant or a priest.

86
00:08:23,413 --> 00:08:28,778
Any intermarriage did not produce a new caste or allow one caste member to move into another caste.

87
00:08:29,519 --> 00:08:32,221
The couple who married became outcasts.

88
00:08:33,562 --> 00:08:40,607
Of course, that society came to its own class system and racist attitudes by way of its own understandings or rather misunderstandings.

89
00:08:40,628 --> 00:08:45,893
But the Buddha asserted that all humans are equal in their ability to escape from ignorance and suffering.

90
00:08:46,548 --> 00:08:53,477
He undermined the whole system by demanding that any person joining his order had to drop all notions of caste.

91
00:08:54,339 --> 00:09:02,571
Even the highest Brahmin, as soon as he joined, joined the end of the armed round even after an untouchable who may have joined but minutes before.

92
00:09:05,596 --> 00:09:13,888
Whatever our ignorance and conditioning were in the past, they are causes now in the present, causes which affect our thinking now.

93
00:09:14,880 --> 00:09:16,864
We can't do anything about them arising.

94
00:09:17,544 --> 00:09:22,291
But by exercising our awareness in daily life, we can begin to see and realize they are there.

95
00:09:23,552 --> 00:09:27,918
Once we begin to do that, we can at least stop them from affecting our actions.

96
00:09:29,380 --> 00:09:36,892
This present ignorance and the present conditioned thoughts and states of mind have been caused by past craving, attachment and action.

97
00:09:37,932 --> 00:09:39,875
At the deepest level, it is these three,

98
00:09:40,294 --> 00:09:52,193
desire, attachment and action, working away and manifesting themselves as our conditionings, that cause us to come into life, that cause us to have and desperately want to keep the body and mind.

99
00:09:54,658 --> 00:10:04,513
Just as ignorant delusion is always present in the mind, just as the volitional conditionings, all our habitual ways of thinking and behaving, are always ready to activate upon a given stimulus,

100
00:10:04,898 --> 00:10:13,990
So the two motivations of craving and attachment, and specifically the will to act upon these motivations, are what create further becoming.

101
00:10:15,150 --> 00:10:20,697
We can begin to see why the Buddha told Ananda off for thinking he had understood this teaching.

102
00:10:21,678 --> 00:10:24,022
We can see here there are wheels within wheels.

103
00:10:24,943 --> 00:10:28,408
The more we study the teaching, the more complicated it becomes.

104
00:10:30,700 --> 00:10:36,428
So now we've got as far as saying that in any given moment of our lives there is an underlying ignorance.

105
00:10:37,250 --> 00:10:41,076
Because of this ignorance, we react to things with craving and attachment.

106
00:10:41,917 --> 00:10:44,821
These cause us to make decisions that produce actions.

107
00:10:45,682 --> 00:10:49,248
These actions, these becomings, build up our conditionings.

108
00:10:50,690 --> 00:10:55,256
All this, all our past, lies pregnant within us at any given moment.

109
00:10:56,114 --> 00:11:00,840
On a life level, it keeps us clinging to life, clinging to our bodies and minds.

110
00:11:01,500 --> 00:11:07,730
In this way, the next five links, consciousness, body and mind, the six senses, sense, contact and feeling, all arise.

111
00:11:08,210 --> 00:11:09,993
And they arise every moment of our lives.

112
00:11:10,754 --> 00:11:15,539
Unfortunately, as soon as they arise, they must go through the process of decay and death.

113
00:11:16,297 --> 00:11:22,163
In this way, the last two links are not only future results of being alive, but are ever present with us now.

114
00:11:22,825 --> 00:11:24,147
Every day begins and ends.

115
00:11:24,846 --> 00:11:26,870
Every moment begins and ends.

116
00:11:29,854 --> 00:11:33,758
We can now begin to understand a little better what the Buddha meant by the doctrine of rebirth.

117
00:11:34,678 --> 00:11:37,663
Firstly, this must not be confused with reincarnation.

118
00:11:38,624 --> 00:11:45,072
Reincarnation presumes that in the body and mind there is a lasting being or substance that carries on unchanged.

119
00:11:45,743 --> 00:11:49,787
What the Buddha discovered was that such an entity did not actually exist.

120
00:11:51,008 --> 00:11:55,292
Everything that goes to make up the body and mind are so many pieces, so many parts.

121
00:11:56,152 --> 00:12:00,115
He divided all these pieces into five categorizations, the five aggregates.

122
00:12:01,216 --> 00:12:11,907
These five aggregates of body, sensations, perceptions, all the volitional conditionings, and consciousness are all arising and passing away at any given moment of the day.

123
00:12:12,626 --> 00:12:13,388
In other words,

124
00:12:13,755 --> 00:12:21,970
This person or being is arising and passing away, being born and dying, every moment of its so-called existence.

125
00:12:23,232 --> 00:12:25,657
The human is this process of change.

126
00:12:26,619 --> 00:12:30,504
This change means that something has to end before something new can begin.

127
00:12:31,567 --> 00:12:34,010
We cannot carry within us the body of the baby.

128
00:12:35,673 --> 00:12:38,919
We were in the body of the adult we are.

129
00:12:39,996 --> 00:12:47,750
That baby body disintegrated soon after birth to give way to the toddler body, and the toddler body gave way to the child body and so on.

130
00:12:48,873 --> 00:12:52,139
Rebirth, in Buddha's understanding, is happening right here and now.

131
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,024
Birth and death are always with us.

132
00:12:56,186 --> 00:13:02,577
It is part of our delusion to see ourselves as always coming into being and never dying out of it.

133
00:13:04,414 --> 00:13:10,163
For this reason, in our meditation, we are encouraged to see not just the beginning but also the ending of things.

134
00:13:11,304 --> 00:13:24,143
In the Mahasatipatthana Sutta, the discourses on the establishment of awareness, where the techniques of insight vipassana meditation are described, the Buddha explains how to observe the breath.

135
00:13:25,884 --> 00:13:33,054
The meditator trains himself to be clearly aware of the whole passage of the in-breath, its beginning, its middle and its end.

136
00:13:33,946 --> 00:13:41,234
He trains himself to be clearly aware of the whole passage of the out-breath, its beginning, its middle, and its end.

137
00:13:44,336 --> 00:13:51,785
When we become more and more aware that all things, meaning ourselves, are constantly dying in the moment, great fear arises.

138
00:13:52,687 --> 00:13:54,808
This is the fear of ego at its own death.

139
00:13:55,889 --> 00:13:58,552
That's why we go into shock if our life is threatened.

140
00:13:59,090 --> 00:14:07,238
This ego, this essential delusion in us, only sees the arising, the birth, the coming into being, the growth, the continuation of things.

141
00:14:08,078 --> 00:14:10,120
It never really looks at the passing of things.

142
00:14:11,221 --> 00:14:14,125
Our culture reinforces this conditioning, this delusion.

143
00:14:14,764 --> 00:14:18,489
We always know the new pop group, the new fashion, the new computer.

144
00:14:19,009 --> 00:14:20,750
We never know what happens to them in the end.

145
00:14:21,072 --> 00:14:21,871
They just disappear.

146
00:14:22,773 --> 00:14:27,577
Their decline and death is blotted out by other new pop groups, fashions, computers.

147
00:14:29,481 --> 00:14:42,616
The inability of our culture to face death, the fact that we hurry the burial, hide the dying, the sick, the deformed, the crippled, are all symptomatic of this ego-blindness, of this fear of decay and death, of our deeply delusive thinking.

148
00:14:43,977 --> 00:14:49,764
All of these reactions to death are based on ignorance, for no one actually knows for sure what happens when we die.

149
00:14:50,725 --> 00:14:52,407
Because we don't know, we imagine.

150
00:14:53,128 --> 00:14:53,908
That's the delusion.

151
00:14:54,649 --> 00:14:55,890
Or we ignore.

152
00:14:56,312 --> 00:14:57,413
That's the ignorance.

153
00:14:58,692 --> 00:15:05,201
But the Buddha, through the teaching of the wheel of dependent origination, is pointing to the now, this ever-present moment.

154
00:15:06,142 --> 00:15:11,669
For it is here and now that we shall capture this stark mixture of birth and death and unravel its secrets.

155
00:15:12,671 --> 00:15:20,261
By unraveling its secrets in the living moment and the dying moment, we will discover what happens upon physical death.

156
00:15:23,076 --> 00:15:31,667
As far as Buddhism is concerned, all that happens upon physical death is that the mind, a different phenomena from body, leaves the body and seeks another.

157
00:15:32,748 --> 00:15:41,938
In this present moment, as you watch your in-breath and out-breath, you will experience sensations caused by the passage of air at the nostrils or the arising and falling of the stomach.

158
00:15:42,799 --> 00:15:47,043
You will see that as the breath comes and goes, consciousness of them arises.

159
00:15:47,745 --> 00:15:49,287
Consciousness arises with it.

160
00:15:49,705 --> 00:15:55,572
The more your meditation deepens, the more you will experience this consciousness as separate from the sensations of breathing.

161
00:15:56,595 --> 00:15:59,698
The meditator comes to know that mind is not body.

162
00:16:00,519 --> 00:16:05,506
But even though this mind leaves the body, it is made up of parts itself, the five aggregates.

163
00:16:06,327 --> 00:16:09,552
There is no entity or soul to be found in these five constituents.

164
00:16:10,833 --> 00:16:17,062
A modern image has been used to explain this phenomena of the mind arising and falling, being born and dying.

165
00:16:18,427 --> 00:16:24,413
When one billiard ball is shot at another and they hit, the first ball stops and the other moves.

166
00:16:24,432 --> 00:16:25,673
What is it that is passed on?

167
00:16:26,774 --> 00:16:28,996
Death is just a mental moment.

168
00:16:29,017 --> 00:16:30,337
It's not the end of anything.

169
00:16:30,837 --> 00:16:32,139
It's the beginning of birth.

170
00:16:33,321 --> 00:16:39,265
When we experience ourselves dying, dying now in meditation, we shall realize death for what it really is.

171
00:16:40,226 --> 00:16:42,889
Just another moment in the cycle of becoming.

172
00:16:44,051 --> 00:16:47,673
Just a point on the ever-turning wheel of dependent origination.

173
00:16:50,422 --> 00:16:55,567
Having said this, let me hasten to add that belief in all this is not necessary for the meditator.

174
00:16:56,009 --> 00:16:58,030
In fact, belief as such is a hindrance.

175
00:16:58,951 --> 00:17:11,788
Whatever you may personally believe or feel about the teaching of rebirth, do remember that all doctrine in Buddhism is put to you as a theory, which is of little value till you yourself prove it for yourself to be true or false.

176
00:17:12,663 --> 00:17:21,361
But at least here you can see that rebirth, not reincarnation, is part and parcel of the Buddha's understanding of how this world of unsatisfactoriness works.

177
00:17:22,123 --> 00:17:27,374
How this ever going on and on, this samsara, turns and turns upon itself.

178
00:17:29,718 --> 00:17:31,903
So where are we on the wheel of dependence origination?

179
00:17:32,980 --> 00:17:44,653
We've seen how our underlying ignorance has been the cause of our craving, attachment and intended actions in the past, which have in turn produced the conditionings that underlie the present moment.

180
00:17:44,673 --> 00:17:55,825
We have seen how the great attachment, our desire for sense pleasure, keeps us clinging to the body and mind, its consciousness, the senses, the sensual contact and the feelings we experience through this.

181
00:17:56,664 --> 00:17:58,126
Now, of course, there's the reaction.

182
00:17:58,984 --> 00:18:04,651
In the present, suddenly presented with incoming data and new sensations, the old conditionings arise.

183
00:18:05,451 --> 00:18:06,574
Suddenly we are craving.

184
00:18:07,334 --> 00:18:08,476
We are becoming attached.

185
00:18:09,537 --> 00:18:14,001
We are making new decisions, creating new karma, reinforcing the volitional conditionings.

186
00:18:14,823 --> 00:18:16,345
This is the dynamic of the wheel.

187
00:18:16,825 --> 00:18:22,171
This dynamic will always produce the future syndrome of birth, growth, decay and death.

188
00:18:23,112 --> 00:18:25,515
So long as we're on this wheel, this is inevitable.

189
00:18:27,689 --> 00:18:30,673
We can see here that this wheel is a historical process.

190
00:18:31,434 --> 00:18:36,122
Things done in the past affect the present, and things done in the present affect the future.

191
00:18:36,561 --> 00:18:37,963
The future becomes the present.

192
00:18:38,404 --> 00:18:39,946
The present becomes the past.

193
00:18:40,488 --> 00:18:43,353
Tomorrow arrives, and today becomes yesterday.

194
00:18:44,795 --> 00:18:50,403
The wheel is also an ever-present process, wherein all factors affect this moment.

195
00:18:50,423 --> 00:18:55,029
By twisting the wheel upon itself, I've tried to give this by way of an image.

196
00:18:55,718 --> 00:19:02,047
It shows that every moment, the now, is a becoming, a coming into being, and with it arises consciousness and the rest.

197
00:19:02,968 --> 00:19:06,973
Twisting it like this also happily gives us the mathematical sign for infinity.

198
00:19:08,234 --> 00:19:24,577
Now that we have come to understand that this wheel is indeed self-propelling, that no beginning was ever designated by the Buddha, nor is an end to this process conceivable, we need to be clear how to escape from it and glimpse, if we can, the life of an arahat, the totally liberated individual.

199
00:19:26,718 --> 00:19:32,246
First of all, we must be absolutely clear on what constitutes a fully enlightened person in terms of the wheel.

200
00:19:32,886 --> 00:19:38,034
It means that there are no more volitional conditionings that are born of desire and attachment.

201
00:19:38,934 --> 00:19:45,704
And it means that there are no more volitional conditionings left in stock that might fuel further actions founded on ignorance.

202
00:19:47,068 --> 00:19:56,699
Remember, this desire is the desire for sense pleasure, and it includes in it the wrong view of self, that this body and mind constitute a permanent substantial being.

203
00:19:58,461 --> 00:20:07,810
Of course, we can't say what an enlightened being thinks about in detail, but we can say that no thoughts, words or actions arise out of this sort of desire or wrong view of self.

204
00:20:08,832 --> 00:20:12,115
Therefore, there is no accumulation of habits that will keep the wheel turning.

205
00:20:13,497 --> 00:20:16,941
Does this mean that the Arahant thinks nothing, says nothing, does nothing?

206
00:20:17,359 --> 00:20:19,584
The more you become enlightened, the more you turn to stone?

207
00:20:20,384 --> 00:20:20,945
Far from it.

208
00:20:21,827 --> 00:20:28,138
If you ever meet someone who is highly spiritually developed, the first thing that strikes you is the presence of that person.

209
00:20:28,159 --> 00:20:29,801
But there's no stereotype.

210
00:20:29,821 --> 00:20:40,701
Depending on past conditioning and experience, that person may be quiet or jovial, or as the famous Bodhidharma, who took Buddhism to the East and is renowned as the founder of Zen, ferocious.

211
00:20:42,132 --> 00:20:47,881
But however that person is, all thoughts and words and actions will arise out of wisdom and not ignorance.

212
00:20:48,942 --> 00:20:57,115
The underlying motivation will therefore not be to satisfy personal desire, but love, compassion, sympathetic joy and peace.

213
00:20:58,999 --> 00:21:07,953
The general state of mind, those sankara, which once gave us so much trouble, are now peaceful and the arahat lives in equanimity.

214
00:21:09,284 --> 00:21:18,758
So long as an enlightened person lives, so long will she or he function as an ordinary human being, with consciousness, body and mind, the six senses, contact and feeling.

215
00:21:19,538 --> 00:21:22,844
They will keep going till all remnants of karma have been consumed.

216
00:21:23,565 --> 00:21:27,330
The Buddha himself lived for 45 years after his enlightenment.

217
00:21:27,351 --> 00:21:29,253
Never does he act out of sense desire.

218
00:21:29,654 --> 00:21:36,625
There is no becoming, there is no karma, good or bad, being accrued, since now there is no ego which can accumulate it.

219
00:21:38,730 --> 00:21:40,692
So how does an enlightened person behave?

220
00:21:41,855 --> 00:21:46,760
When we read the scriptures, we read how forthright and direct the Buddha was with monks who did wrong.

221
00:21:47,902 --> 00:21:56,051
When Suddhinā, a monk who was enticed by his family to make love with his former wife so that there be an heir, the Buddha rebukes him.

222
00:21:57,012 --> 00:21:58,634
It is not fit, foolish man.

223
00:21:59,056 --> 00:21:59,936
It is not becoming.

224
00:22:00,057 --> 00:22:00,958
It is not proper.

225
00:22:00,978 --> 00:22:02,599
It is unworthy of a recluse.

226
00:22:02,740 --> 00:22:03,560
It is unlawful.

227
00:22:04,001 --> 00:22:05,143
It ought not to be done.

228
00:22:06,051 --> 00:22:10,938
The Buddha goes on to explain why this is so, calling him a foolish man no less than 15 times.

229
00:22:11,298 --> 00:22:12,220
It's a real tirade.

230
00:22:13,500 --> 00:22:17,886
On the other hand, when he deals with Paticcara, who has lost a family, he's full of compassion.

231
00:22:18,807 --> 00:22:23,614
When he talks to Potapada about philosophical questions, you can sense his gentle mirth.

232
00:22:24,836 --> 00:22:29,981
When he wants to search out somewhere pleasant to eat his meal, a pleasant grove, you can see he appreciates beauty.

233
00:22:31,284 --> 00:22:35,890
The fact that the kings of the time came to him for advice shows the sort of figure he cut in public.

234
00:22:36,780 --> 00:22:45,710
All we can say of a fully enlightened being, a Buddha or an Arahant, is that all their actions arise out of wisdom and not out of ignorant self-gratification of desires.

235
00:22:47,250 --> 00:22:55,259
That their mental states are in one of the four modes, either of equanimity, sympathetic joy, universal love or compassion.

236
00:22:57,902 --> 00:22:59,784
How does this square up with the law of karma?

237
00:23:00,565 --> 00:23:05,910
Again, it is recognizing the two pools into which the stones of thought, speech and action drop.

238
00:23:06,750 --> 00:23:09,094
The Buddha was constantly affecting people around him.

239
00:23:09,294 --> 00:23:10,134
Indeed, he still is.

240
00:23:10,976 --> 00:23:13,138
But within his own mind, there are no ripples.

241
00:23:14,059 --> 00:23:19,968
There is no reaction, no conditioned response, no response at all that arises out of a wrong view of a self.

242
00:23:20,888 --> 00:23:25,894
Therefore, this self or ego or idea of a substantial personality is simply not there.

243
00:23:26,895 --> 00:23:30,800
Because the enlightened behave with wisdom, so they affect the world around them.

244
00:23:31,422 --> 00:23:34,445
And these effects move the world towards peace and harmony.

245
00:23:35,371 --> 00:23:37,934
What happens then to a Buddha or an Arahant after death?

246
00:23:38,695 --> 00:23:40,478
The Buddha said it was indescribable.

247
00:23:41,519 --> 00:23:46,266
But an Arahant may be reborn in a higher realm till all his residual karma is worn out.

248
00:23:46,826 --> 00:23:49,830
Then he passes into parinibbana, total nibbana.

249
00:23:51,712 --> 00:23:58,001
So we have seen how the wheel of dependent origination fits together as a historical process and as an immediate happening.

250
00:23:59,183 --> 00:24:01,446
We see how it includes the teaching of rebirth.

251
00:24:02,387 --> 00:24:03,910
So where does all this leave us?

252
00:24:04,852 --> 00:24:08,395
Needless to say, it leaves us right here and now, spinning round and round.

253
00:24:09,497 --> 00:24:20,470
Whatever personal opinions we come to concerning rebirth or enlightenment, one thing we can test for ourselves right here and now is whether desire and attachment are truly the causes of our unhappiness.

254
00:24:21,872 --> 00:24:27,638
That we can test by the practice of vipassana insight meditation and the daily effort to be mindful.

255
00:24:28,278 --> 00:24:32,344
We can discover where the exit lies, where the escape is to be found.

256
00:24:32,746 --> 00:24:37,073
right there between feelings and the desire for them.

257
00:24:37,093 --> 00:24:50,794
How important it is to grasp this fact, to really realize for ourselves the difference between pleasant, unpleasant and neutral feelings and our desire or aversion for them.

258
00:24:50,814 --> 00:24:56,863
How important it is to realize that we lose nothing but suffering in giving up these desires and attachments.

259
00:24:57,501 --> 00:25:08,614
Indeed, that we can gain peace of mind, joy, and a boundless ability to be loving and compassionate once we do drop this self-centeredness, this continual desire to satisfy our desires.

260
00:25:10,134 --> 00:25:13,759
How important it is to realize that this moment is all we have.

261
00:25:14,700 --> 00:25:20,465
We can only do something about ourselves, about our situation, in the present moment, the now.

262
00:25:21,326 --> 00:25:26,412
This moment now is the fruit of all our past, the seed of all our future.

263
00:25:27,049 --> 00:25:31,473
We only have this moment to change past direction, to create new direction.

264
00:25:32,474 --> 00:25:36,278
Let that direction be from darkness to light, and from light to light.

265
00:25:36,778 --> 00:25:39,942
We must resolve to purify our hearts and minds.

266
00:25:42,244 --> 00:25:47,249
Here is a lovely verse from the verses of the sisters, the nuns, the bhikkhuni, who achieved arahatship.

267
00:25:47,769 --> 00:25:48,770
I recommend their reading.

268
00:25:49,010 --> 00:25:49,852
They are inspiring.

269
00:25:50,913 --> 00:25:56,397
Sundari Nanda was a beautiful woman, it seems, greatly caught up in her physical beauty and sensual desire.

270
00:25:57,019 --> 00:26:02,967
She used the meditations on aging and death to overcome her great attachment, and eventually she won the goal.

271
00:26:04,788 --> 00:26:11,436
I, even I, have seen from the inside and outside this body as it indeed really is.

272
00:26:12,638 --> 00:26:17,144
I strive to know the what and why of it with unfaltering zeal and fiery ardor.

273
00:26:18,346 --> 00:26:23,432
Now I care no more for this body and all my consciousness is free of passion.

274
00:26:24,509 --> 00:26:26,213
Keen with unfettered zeal.

275
00:26:26,914 --> 00:26:28,861
No attachments.

276
00:26:28,881 --> 00:26:29,903
Calm and serene.

277
00:26:30,645 --> 00:26:36,441
I taste the peace of Nibbana.

278
00:26:36,461 --> 00:26:39,750
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

